<H1>Considerations for Internet Drafts:</H1>
<DIR>Here is a list of common "nits" that have been known to stop =
documents in=20
the IESG. This list does not pretend to cover all questions, especially =
content=20
questions like "does it work?", "is it bad for the Internet", etc. It =
does cover=20
some of the lower level issues that come up.</DIR>
<H2>But does it work?</H2>
<DIR>That said, "does it work" includes a number of questions about =
operation in=20
the Internet. If you are designing a protocol or an operational =
specification,=20
it would be good to ask yourself a number of questions about your =
proposal - you=20
can save yourself some grief by a few moments cautious consideration =
of:</DIR>
<UL>
  <LI>What happens if this is implemented in a service provider's =
network? Some=20
  companies have larger internal corporate networks (what it is now =
fashionable=20
  to call "intranets") than many for-profit service provider networks. A =
large=20
  percentage of security problems derive from within the network that is =

  attacked. The statement "security and scaling issues are handled at =
the=20
  firewall; this is just for corporate networks" doesn't wash. Are there =
likely=20
  to be policy issues between competing service providers, or between an =
edge=20
  network and its service provider? Will security issues arise?=20
  <LI>Take a glance at the <A=20
  href=3D"http://www.isi.edu/in-notes/rfc1958.txt">Architectural =
Principles of the=20
  Internet</A>. Can it be said that your proposal violates fundamental =
concepts=20
  like: </LI></UL>
<DIR>
<DL>
  <DT>End to End Principle=20
  <DD>The argument for retaining simplicity and flexibility in the =
Internet by=20
  keeping state out of the network or (at worst) limiting it to =
well-defined=20
  points in the network.=20
  <DT>Heterogeneity apart from the network layer=20
  <DD>Recognition of differing needs and points of view, and therefore =
differing=20
  protocol choices by network administrations=20
  <DT>One end to end inter-network protocol=20
  <DD>Perhaps the architecture should be updated to mention IP4 and IP6 =
in one=20
  breath, but it does expect that there is one internet protocol end to =
end, and=20
  that little else is ubiquitous. </DD></DL></DIR>
<UL>
  <LI>Have you done any interoperability testing between independent=20
  implementations? Such testing is always a Good Thing To Do, even at =
the very=20
  earliest stages. It should emphasize not only testing for correct =
behavior,=20
  but also testing for robust response to incorrect messages or =
behaviors.=20
</LI></UL>
<H2>Think about security before sending it to the IESG</H2>
<DIR>Frankly, the Security Area Directors will be happier with you if =
you think=20
about security while designing the protocol, so they don't have to ask a =
lot of=20
whiny-sounding questions. You might read <A=20
href=3D"http://www.isi.edu/in-notes/rfc2316.txt">Report of the IAB =
Security=20
Architecture Workshop</A>. It is often worthwhile to ask someone who has =
written=20
an RFC that you think has a good security considerations section to =
review your=20
draft well before you think you are finished.</DIR>
<UL>
  <LI>Does your document take into consideration common cryptanalytic =
techniques=20
  and scenarios, such as spoofing, denial-of-service, man-in-the-middle =
attacks,=20
  message re-ordering, message replay, adaptive chosen plaintext or =
ciphertext=20
  attacks, and so on?=20
  <LI>If there are several choices for a particular algorithm, =
mechanism, or=20
  technique, does your document make clear what the security trade-offs =
are?=20
  <LI>If some technique or protocol in your document is intended to =
provide a=20
  security service (such as authentication, integrity, confidentiality, =
and so=20
  on), has this been reviewed by persons other than the authors (e.g.,=20
  cryptanalysts or persons with a strong security background)? Is this =
review=20
  public (i.e., are there references to journal papers, conference=20
  presentations, or technical reports)?=20
  <LI>How is secrecy of information protected against malicious third =
party? How=20
  do you authenticate the other party you are communicating with, and =
messages=20
  from it? How do you avoid Man-in-the-middle attacks? How do you trust =
and=20
  authorize the authenticated party?=20
  <LI>Are there any known security deficiencies or weaknesses in the =
protocol=20
  described in your document, or any areas that still require review and =

  analysis? Consider: </LI></UL>
<DIR>
<DT><B>Threats:</B>=20
<DD>Privacy, of both data and system usage.=20
<DD>Resistance to denial of service attack=20
<DD>Trustworthiness of results.=20
<DD>Susceptibility to inadvertent misconfiguration.=20
<DD>Susceptibility to malicious attack.=20
<DT><B>Assumptions/applicability:</B>=20
<DD>Use for valuable data or mission-critical functions.=20
<DD>Use in constrained operating environment.=20
<DT><B>Countermeasures, implementation requirements:</B>=20
<DD>What additional issues should implementers address?=20
<DD>What additional issues should deployment address?=20
<DD>Use in combination with other protocols.=20
<P>Does your document have an adequate security considerations section? =
Some=20
have said that the "Security Considerations" section of a document =
essentially=20
helps hackers attack implementations. It may, but the fact is that they =
will do=20
the analysis themselves anyway - not doing a threat analysis will not =
stop them=20
from exploiting weaknesses in your design. But by pointing out design =
choices=20
you have made which have security implications, or by documenting "when =
you=20
implement this, you should make these choices that have security =
implications",=20
you may help people build implementations that are more hacker-proof, =
and you=20
may find something you can improve. Frankly, the IESG has so many =
documents come=20
its way which have no thought for security in them it must return for =
the=20
analysis, putting the analysis into the document will be helpful in =
getting it=20
through.</P></DD></DIR>
