<H2>IANA considerations</H2>
<DIR>If you are defining a new TCP or UDP port, RSVP object, Telnet =
option, PPP=20
PID, etc., go to <A href=3D"http://www.iana.org/">IANA</A>, click on =
"application=20
forms" and then on the appropriate form type, and fill in the blanks. =
You can=20
get the option assigned experimentally long before turning the Internet =
Draft=20
into an RFC, which saves you flag days and the like. You should get the =
working=20
group chair's buy-in before getting a standard port number or option, =
though, as=20
he or she will likely be polled by IANA and you don't want him surprised =
by the=20
request.=20
<P>If you are defining a field that IANA will need to assign instances =
of, read=20
and follow <A href=3D"http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2434.txt">Guidelines =
for Writing=20
an IANA Considerations Section in RFCs </A>and write one into your=20
document.</P></DIR>
<H2>Use of requirements language</H2>
<DIR>Generally, MUST/MAY/SHOULD usage should be normalized by a =
reference to <A=20
href=3D"http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2119.txt">RFC 2119 </A>called out in =
proper=20
place in text, i.e., at the front, rather than at the end. Note that the =

abstract in RFC 2119 contains the wording you should use when referring =
to RFC=20
2119.=20
<P>It is OK for an Internet Draft to define MAY/MUST/SHOULD itself, but =
it <A=20
href=3D"http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2119.txt">SHOULD</A> have a reason =
they do not=20
use 2119 - the SMTP update document is an example where there was a =
legitimate=20
reason to do local definitions=20
<P>Note, by the way, that few documents really specify requirements, and =
should=20
therefore be using requirements language. If you are specifying a =
protocol, you=20
probably don't mean that "the implementation MUST do this certain thing" =
in a=20
"requirements" sense, but "a correct implementation will do this certain =
thing,=20
because=85" there is a technical reason it needs to do so. Don't replace =
clear=20
concise prose with requirements language.</P></DIR>
<H2>Updating or obsoleting RFCs</H2>
<DIR>For documents replacing/updating existing RFCs, include an appendix =
(not a=20
section) listing changes relative to previous RFC. The abstract and/or =
the=20
introduction should also summarize what is being updated or obsoleted. =
The=20
"obsoletes" header isn't good enough, you want it in the text where the =
reader=20
can't miss it.</DIR>
<H2>References in Internet Drafts</H2>
<DIR>When publishing an Internet Draft onto the standards track, are =
there any=20
dependencies on documents that are still drafts and/or not standards =
track, or=20
lower grade? Non-normative references are OK, but normative references =
(those=20
that must be read and understood to correctly understand or implement =
the=20
specification) to documentation that may not be readily available are =
not.=20
<P>Consider especially whether ITU-T or related organizations may refer =
to your=20
draft as normative. If they do, their reference rules apply as =
well.</P></DIR>
<H2>Publication status</H2>
<DIR>In your note to an Area Director requesting advancement of a =
document to a=20
certain status, is the requested publication status appropriate? <A=20
href=3D"http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2026.txt">BCP 9 </A>indicates what =
the relevant=20
issues are, but consider this:=20
<DL>
  <DT><B>Informational</B>=20
  <DD>An "informational" specification is published for the general =
information=20
  of the Internet community, but does not represent an Internet =
community=20
  consensus or recommendation. It may describe architecture, and be =
accompanied=20
  by standards track protocol specifications; it may be an applicability =

  statement on a protocol or procedure. It may be a white paper, a =
corporate=20
  statement of direction, a poem, or an April Fool's joke. The =
Informational=20
  designation is intended to provide for the timely publication of a =
very broad=20
  range of responsible informational documents from many sources, =
subject only=20
  to editorial considerations and to verification that there has been =
adequate=20
  coordination with the standards process.=20
  <DD>"Informational" status is often abused by people wishing to bypass =
the=20
  standards process or post promotional literature. Because of this =
practice,=20
  these documents are now reviewed by the IESG even if they are simply =
sent to=20
  the RFC Editor. The IESG often simply publishes the document. It may =
ask for=20
  minor modifications such as the addition of a company's name to the =
title=20
  ("The Way To Build A Framistat" becomes "FUBAR Corporation's Design =
For A=20
  Framistat"), or editorial changes. It may add what is called an "IESG =
Note",=20
  like "This document is probably a reasonable thing to do, but it has =
had no=20
  review and does not represent a consensus by an IETF working group". =
It may=20
  recommend that the document not be published. In this last case, it =
will state=20
  why that decision was made, and the decision may be debated with the =
area=20
  director, IESG Chair, or the IAB as appropriate.=20
  <DT><B>Historic</B>=20
  <DD>A specification that has been superseded by a more recent =
specification or=20
  is for any other reason considered obsolete.=20
  <DT><B>Experimental</B>=20
  <DD>The "Experimental" designation typically denotes a specification =
that is=20
  part of some research or development effort, and not intended for =
general=20
  implementation apart from participation in that effort. Such a =
specification=20
  is published for the general information of the Internet technical =
community=20
  and as an archival record of the work, subject only to editorial=20
  considerations and to verification that there has been adequate =
coordination=20
  with the standards process (see below). An Experimental specification =
may be=20
  the output of an organized Internet research effort (e.g., a Research =
Group of=20
  the IRTF), an IETF Working Group, or it may be an individual =
contribution.=20
  <DT><B>Proposed Standard</B>=20
  <DD>A Proposed Standard specification is generally stable, has =
resolved known=20
  design choices, is believed to be well-understood, has received =
significant=20
  community review, and appears to enjoy enough community interest to be =

  considered valuable. However, further experience might result in a =
change or=20
  even retraction of the specification before it advances.=20
  <DD>It is possible for a document to go straight from an individual =
submission=20
  to Proposed Standard without review by a working group. To accomplish =
that,=20
  one must get the backing of an Area Director, and the IETF performs a=20
  four-week last call instead of the usual two-week last call. This =
process path=20
  is, however, unusual, as something that needs Proposed Standard status =
by=20
  definition needs multiple implementers agreeing on a specification, =
and=20
  generally, they need to talk about the specification.=20
  <DT><B>Draft Standard</B>=20
  <DD>A specification from which at least two independent and =
interoperable=20
  implementations from different code bases have been developed, and for =
which=20
  sufficient successful operational experience has been obtained, may be =

  elevated to the "Draft Standard" level. For the purposes of this =
section,=20
  "interoperable" means to be functionally equivalent or interchangeable =

  components of the system or process in which they are used. If =
patented or=20
  otherwise controlled technology is required for implementation, the =
separate=20
  implementations must also have resulted from separate exercise of the=20
  licensing process.=20
  <DD>Elevation to Draft Standard is a major advance in status, =
indicating a=20
  strong belief that the specification is mature and will be useful.=20
  <DT><B>Internet (Full) Standard</B>=20
  <DD>A specification for which significant implementation and =
successful=20
  operational experience has been obtained may be elevated to the =
Internet=20
  Standard level. An Internet Standard (which may simply be referred to =
as a=20
  Standard) is characterized by a high degree of technical maturity and =
by a=20
  generally held belief that the specified protocol or service provides=20
  significant benefit to the Internet community.=20
  <DT><B>Best Current Practice</B>=20
  <DD>The BCP series is designed to be a way to standardize practices =
and the=20
  results of community deliberations. A BCP document is subject to the =
same=20
  basic set of procedures as standards track documents. It is thus is a =
vehicle=20
  by which the IETF community can define and ratify the community's best =
current=20
  thinking on a statement of principle or on what is believed to be the =
best way=20
  to perform some operations or IETF process function. </DD></DL></DIR>
<H2>Document title</H2>
<DIR>Is the title appropriate (i.e., accurate, not misleading, etc.)?=20
<P>The words <B>requirements</B> and <B>standard</B> are red flags when =
found in=20
document titles; unless this is a working group document, those words =
are=20
probably not your best choices. In addition, if your document describes =
a=20
proprietary product, the title should clearly say that.</P></DIR>
<H2>Relationship with common architectural issues</H2>
<DIR>How does your proposal relate to certain aspects that we find =
common in the=20
Internet, or expect to in the near future, such as:</DIR>
<UL>
  <UL>
    <LI>Network Address Translators (NATs)=20
    <LI>IP Version 6=20
    <LI>Fire walls=20
    <LI>Underlying transports </LI></UL></UL>
<DIR>Note, in asking these questions, we're not saying "IP6 Rules", or =
"NATs are=20
good/bad" or anything of the sort. We are saying that IP6 deployment is=20
something we consider likely to be important tomorrow, and NATs and Fire =
walls=20
are realities that we live with today. If your MIB, protocol, or =
procedure=20
doesn't have a clear and well thought-out way to address these issues, =
it is=20
limited in applicability.=20
<P>It may be that you have designed a solution to a problem that occurs=20
primarily in corporate networks, and so would be used mostly behind a =
firewall.=20
However, if it has to <B>remain</B> behind a firewall to be viable, it =
would be=20
a good idea to say why this is so, in the Security Considerations. You =
should=20
also plan a second version that fixes them. The IESG and your customers =
are very=20
likely to consider these issues to be bugs in the specification, =
sufficient to=20
force it off the standards track into "experimental" or "not recommended =
for=20
production usage".=20
<P>The reason for this is that corporate intranets are in some cases =
larger than=20
service provider networks, and a large percentage (on the order of 80%) =
of=20
attacks come from within the affected network. So firewalls cannot be =
expected=20
to provide security, only a perimeter that limits the <B>external</B> =
exposure=20
of the organization. </P></DIR>
<H2>Intellectual property</H2>
<DIR>Are there intellectual property issues? Does the document actually =
mention=20
Intellectual Property Rights prior to last call? Do you conform to the=20
Intellectual Property Rights guidelines in section 10 of <A=20
href=3D"http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2026.txt">BCP 9</A>, which among =
other things=20
states that "The contributor represents that he has disclosed the =
existence of=20
any proprietary or intellectual property rights in the contribution that =
are=20
reasonably and personally known to the contributor." RFC 2026 makes many =
other=20
requirements on RFC editors and contributors; be sure to read it =
carefully=20
before your draft has gone to the IESG.=20
<P>References to a do not include references to particular IPR (patents =
or=20
patents that have been applied for) should not be in the Internet Draft. =

Instead, be sure to include the text from rfc 2026 that applies to your =
document=20
and situation. Be sure to send notices of any IPR relevent to the ID to =
the IETF=20
Executive Director <IESG-SECRETARY@IETF.ORG>for inclusion on the IPR=20
page</P></DIR>
<H2>Service issues</H2>
<DIR>IP over your favorite link layer, and IP over specific IP service=20
documents, might ask themselves these questions:</DIR>
<UL>
  <LI>How does this use or support multicast or broadcast? Is something =
special=20
  required in the presence of a Virtual LAN? If something special is =
required,=20
  say so.=20
  <LI>Does this use or make special requirements on IP address =
resolution?=20
  <LI>How will it be affected by IP Version 6? If it is more than "it =
just=20
  works", the draft should indicate what is required to make IP6 work.=20
  <LI>How will it be administered? Are there any assumptions that need =
to be=20
  documented?=20
  <LI>Is there any example of the intended use? It may be obvious to the =

  authors, but not necessarily to anyone else. </LI></UL>
<H2>For documents advancing in grade</H2>
<UL>
  <LI>The IESG will want to read your implementation report, which is =
expected=20
  to indicate who tested the products and what features were tested in =
each=20
  implementation.=20
  <LI>Make sure there are no normative references to documents at lower =
grade. A=20
  "normative" reference leads to another document required to correctly=20
  understand or implement a specification. A "non-normative" reference =
leads to=20
  material that may be helpful or educational, but is not required. =
</LI></UL>
<DIR>At least two complete, independent implementations must be tested =
and=20
reported on, of each role (client/server/peer), and of each feature. If=20
intellectual property must be licensed, BCP 9 requires that the =
implementations=20
derive from separate licenses.</DIR>
<H2>Internationalization</H2>
<H3>Language</H3>
<DIR>Does your protocol need to exchange language information between =
client and=20
server? If so, can it? Language information definitions can be found in =
<A=20
href=3D"http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc1766.txt">RFC 1766</A>.</DIR>
<H3>Localization</H3>
<DIR>Is there trouble regarding data (addresses, date, time, number) =
formats in=20
presentation? Are you using a "year 2000 compliant" format? Is storage =
specified=20
in a way so it is unambiguous, so presentation formats can be left as an =

exercise to the presentation layer?</DIR>
<H3>Character sets</H3>
<DIR>Is it clear how UTF-8 is handled? In addition, if other character =
sets are=20
allowed/used, how is the character set negotiated/specified? Information =
on=20
character set issues can be found in <A=20
href=3D"http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2130.txt">The Report of the IAB =
Character Set=20
Workshop</A> and in the <A =
href=3D"http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2277.txt">IETF=20
Policy on Character Sets and Languages</A>.</DIR>
<H2>Independent submissions</H2>
<DIR>If the document does not come from an IETF working group, and =
especially if=20
it is a single-company document, the IESG will pay special attention and =
is=20
likely to arrange some form of third-party review. If there is a working =
group=20
chartered in the area, it is very likely to be the working group. Be =
prepared to=20
revise the draft accordingly. Proprietary specifications, if published =
as=20
Informational RFCs, must include the name of the company or association=20
responsible for the specification in the title.</DIR>
<H2>Management Information Base submissions (MIBs)</H2>
<DIR>You might start out by perusing <A =
href=3D"http://www.ops.ietf.org/">The=20
Operations and Management Area Web Page</A></DIR>
<UL>
  <LI>Make sure that your MIB compiles cleanly with at least one =
(preferably=20
  multiple) MIB compilers.=20
  <LI>Make sure you have the proper MIB boilerplate (see <A=20
  href=3D"http://www.ops.ietf.org/mib-boilerplate.html">MIB =
Boilerplate</A>)=20
  <LI>Make sure you specify which objects are sensitive in the MIB and =
how to=20
  protect them via access control. (see <A=20
  href=3D"http://www.ops.ietf.org/security.html">MIB Security</A>)=20
  <LI>Make sure you have proper REVISION clauses in the MIB in the=20
  MODULE-IDENTITY macro invocation.=20
  <LI>Make sure you adhere to the SMIv2 rules as defined in RFCs <A=20
  href=3D"http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2578.txt">2578</A>, <A=20
  href=3D"http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2579.txt">2579</A> and <A=20
  href=3D"http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2580.txt">2580</A> (STD 58) =
</LI></UL>
<H2>Variant Algorithm Definitions</H2><B>If you specify multiple =
algorithms for=20
a particular function</B>=20
<DIR>For example, if there are multiple compression algorithms, =
encryption=20
algorithms, representation formats, etc., consider</DIR>
<UL>
  <LI>A robust way to enumerate these, preferably with space for future=20
  assignments by the <A href=3D"http://www.iana.org/">Internet Assigned =
Number=20
  Authority</A>=20
  <LI>Consider re-using an existing IANA registry instead of creating a =
new one,=20
  since this leads to less confusion between different registries that =
have=20
  similar items.=20
  <LI>Designating one as "mandatory to implement". This algorithm should =
be of=20
  sufficient quality for the purpose and be unencumbered by intellectual =

  property rights, if possible. If a single mandatory algorithm cannot =
be=20
  chosen, state why. </LI></UL>
<H3>Undefined and ambiguous text</H3>
<DIR>If a standard contains functions which are not fully defined, this =
may=20
cause different implementors to interpret these functions in different =
ways,=20
which will cause interoperability problems. Because of this, you are =
strongly=20
advised to try to avoid anything that is undefined or ambiguous. In =
particular,=20
it is <U>not</U> a good solution to disagreements in a standards =
development=20
group, to resolve the disagreements by leaving something unclear, vague, =

ambiguous or undefined.=20
<P>If, however, you absolutely need to have something undefined, you =
should at=20
least clearly specify what is undefined, and why.</P></DIR>
<H1>Notes on the IESG review procedure</H1>
<H2>Naming your Internet Draft</H2>
<DIR>The IETF generally uses this convention for Internet Draft file =
names. NN=20
is a sequence number, starting from 00 and monotonically increasing. =
<BR>&nbsp;=20
<DL>
  <DT><B>Independent submissions</B>:=20
  <DD>Draft-&lt;author name&gt;-&lt;descriptive text&gt;-NN.txt=20
  <DD>Example: draft-baker-spam-what-am-00.txt=20
  <DT><B>Independent submissions to a working group</B>=20
  <DD>Draft-&lt;author name&gt;-&lt;working group&gt;-&lt;descriptive=20
  text&gt;-NN.txt=20
  <DD>Example: draft-baker-spamwg-spam-what-am-not-00.txt=20
  <DT><B>Working Group documents</B>=20
  <DD>Draft-ietf-&lt;working group&gt;-descriptive text&gt;-NN.txt=20
  <DD>Example: draft-ietf-spamwg-how-to-send-spam-00.txt </DD></DL>You =
must have=20
the consent of your working group chair, and the working charter needs =
to have a=20
corresponding work item, to consider your document a working group =
document.=20
Individual submissions (whether general or to a working group) may be =
made=20
without prior notice, but unless you ask someone to do something with =
them,=20
nothing further will be done.</DIR>
<H2>Submitting your Internet Draft</H2>
<DIR>Please assure that the boilerplate specified in <A=20
href=3D"http://www.ietf.org/ietf/1id-guidelines.txt">Internet Draft =
Guidelines</A>=20
is present.=20
<P>Additionally, here are some comments from <A=20
href=3D"http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2223.txt">Instructions to RFC =
Authors</A>,=20
which you should read:</P></DIR>
<UL>
  <UL>
    <LI>Documents should not be right justified, (i.e., not filled) or=20
    hyphenated.=20
    <LI>Make sure that special characters "'", """, "-" come through as =
ASCII,=20
    not word processor control characters.=20
    <LI>If there is a postscript version of the file, make sure that an =
ASCII=20
    version also exists and that the protocol or proposal can be equally =

    implemented from either. </LI></UL></UL>
<DIR>Having put your document together, you can email it, either as text =
or as=20
an attachment, to <A=20
href=3D"mailto:internet-drafts@ietf.org">internet-drafts@ietf.org</A>.=20
Alternatively, you may post it as an FTP-accessible file and mail the =
URL to the=20
same address. The latter is nicer for the person managing the Internet =
Drafts=20
directory.=20
<P>In general, you may post Internet Drafts whenever they are =
appropriate to a=20
discussion or idea. If they are intended for discussion during an IETF =
Working=20
Group meeting, there is an Internet Draft cut-off roughly a month prior =
to the=20
meeting. This is intended to allow people time to read the proposals, =
promoting=20
intelligent discussion, and most working group chairs require that =
documents for=20
discussion must be posted, or give first consideration to posted=20
documents.</P></DIR>
<H2>Responding to IESG requests for changes</H2>
<DIR>The IESG often requests that changes be made to an Internet Draft =
before it=20
moves to the RFC Editor. If this happens, make the requested changes in =
a new=20
revision of the draft, submit the new draft through the normal =
draft-submission=20
procedures, and let the Area Director responsible for the draft know =
when the=20
submission has been made available in the official Internet Drafts=20
directory.</DIR>
<H2>Communicating with the sponsoring area director</H2>
<DIR>The amount and kind of communication that you will have with the =
Area=20
Director who is sponsoring your draft will depend on many factors. These =
include=20
whether the draft is a WG item or an individual submission, whether or =
not you=20
and the Area Director agree on the changes requested by the IESG, the=20
criticality of the other drafts that the Area Director is sponsoring, =
and the=20
Area Director's other duties.</DIR>
<H2>I need to change a draft after I have submitted it to the IESG</H2>
<DIR>That's OK, as long as the draft has not been officially processed =
and=20
approved. If you need to make changes, submit a new revision of the =
draft=20
through the normal draft-submission procedures. You should probably let =
the=20
sponsoring Area Director know as soon as you know that you are going to =
be=20
submitting a new draft so he or she can suspend the process on the =
current one.=20
<P>Once the draft has been considered by the IESG, changes are not =
particularly=20
welcome, although they may be required. The IESG handles these events on =
a case=20
by case basis, often asking the relevant working group to review the =
changes and=20
repeat the submission.</P></DIR>
<HR>

<P>Last updated by <A href=3D"mailto:iesg@ietf.org">Fred Baker</A> on =
April 27=20
1999.=20
<P>The original text came from notes from Thomas Narten, Bert Wijnen, =
and Patrik=20
F&auml;ltstr&ouml;m. Significant editorial work was done by Paul =
Hoffman, and subject and=20
content review was done by quite a number of recent Internet Draft =
authors. No=20
representation is made that we have thought of everything you need to =
know, or=20
that we won't think of improvements, but this should help. Additional =
questions=20
and suggestions should be placed to the <A =
href=3D"mailto:iesg@ietf.org">IESG</A>=20
or to the <A href=3D"mailto:poised@lists.tislabs.com">Poisson working =
group</A>. <!-- ZoneLabs Popup Blocking Insertion -->
